<TITLE> Court summons Amar Desh acting editor </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 30 (bdnews24.com)  A Dhaka court has summoned daily Amar Desh acting editor Mahmudur Rahman by June 10 in a defamation case. Chief metropolitan magistrate Abdul Mazid gave the order on a case filed by film director Morshedul Islam on Sunday over a report published in the Bengali newspaper. Islam is the brother of law state minister Qamrul Islam. Other defendants are publisher Md Hashmat Ali and reporters MA Noman and Raqib Hossain. They have also been ordered to appear before the court. In his statement, Islam said that two reports published on May 27 and 28 stated that his brother Qamrul Islam as a Razakar  a term ascribed to those who collaborated with the Pakistani Army during Bangladesh's Liberation War in 1971. The reports also termed Islam's family as a Razakar family, he said in the complaint. The reports had defamed him as the brother of the state minister, he said. Islam said his brother took part in the Liberation War after getting training under the first batch of Bangladesh Liberation Force from India's military academy. His father Khorshedul Islam and brother Azizul Islam were unani doctors. Islam's films have been acknowledged locally and internationally. Among the films are Agami, Suchana, Chaka, Dukhai and Dipu Number 2. He said the Liberation War was a major source of inspiration for his films. State minister Qamrul Islam is the joint general secretary of Dhaka metropolitan Awami League. bdn
